Que 5. What is the difference between intermediate and terminal operations in Streams?
Ans: Intermediate operations transform a stream into another stream. Its return type always a new stream.
		Some common intermediate operation are include below:
		filter(): It is filter the elements based on the specified conditions.
			stream.filter(n -> n > 7)
		map(): Transform each element in a stream to another value.
			stream.map(n -> n + 2)
		sorted(): It is sorted the elements of a stream.
			stream.sorted()
		distinct(): Its remove the duplicate element from the stream.
			stream.distinct
		peek(): its perform the action without changing stream.
			stream.peek(Systen.out::println)
			
		
		Terminal operations are the operations that on execution return a final result as an absolute value.
		Once it is called, the stream is traversed and consumed.
		We cannot reuse a stream after a terminal operation has been performed.
		Common examples:
			collect() - It is used to return the result of the intermediate operations performed on the stream.
				stream.collect(Collection.toList())
			forEach() - It iterates all the element in a stream.
				stream.forEach(System.out::println)
			reduce() - it is used to reduce the elements of a stream to a single value.
				stream.reduce(0, Integer::sum)
			count() - It is return the count of the element in stream.
				stream.count()

